    "Equation (7)) but more heterogeneous in their gross benefits from the tools (i.e., when β b is large in absolute value, implying that marginal users have lower idiosyncratic benefits).",
    "Second, employer initiatives that increase benefits (α b) have two offsetting effects on average reported benefits.",
    "On the one hand, a higher α b directly raises each user's individual benefit B i.",
    "On the other hand, it expands adoption, drawing in users with lower idiosyncratic benefits (i.e., higher i), thereby triggering the same negative selection effect as a reduction in α c.",
    "The net effect of an increase in α b on the average reported benefits among users B is positive if and only if γ < 1."
